      "acceptanceCriteria": "Newton-Raphson nonlinear solver convergence criteria: force residual < 0.1% and displacement residual < 0.1% at each load step. No unconverged increments in production runs.",
      "rationale": "All production analyses converged within specified tolerances. Maximum force residual observed was 0.04% across 11 model instances. No load step bisections required beyond standard automatic stepping. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent review of model setup by a second analyst. Boundary conditions, contact definitions, and material assignments verified against the modeling protocol document.",
      "rationale": "Model setup reviewed by a second FEA analyst not involved in original model construction. Boundary conditions (fixed inferior vertebral body, axial-bending load applied at superior body centroid) confirmed consistent with ASTM F1717 test configuration. No discrepancies identified. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Constitutive model selection justified by material characterization data. Isotropic linear elasticity with bilinear kinematic hardening for titanium alloy Ti-6Al-4V confirmed adequate for quasi-static loading regime.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material behavior under quasi-static compression-bending is well characterized in the literature. Bilinear kinematic hardening parameters derived from coupon tensile tests (n=6). Comparison of predicted vs. measured load-displacement curves shows correct slope and yield point prediction. Model form uncertainty assessed as low. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric dimensions sourced from direct measurements on test articles. Input uncertainty characterized by Monte Carlo UQ propagation across 1000 samples. A screening sensitivity study was documented in the UQ appendix to identify potentially dominant parameters.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus (E = 113.8 ± 2.1 GPa), yield strength (Sy = 924 ± 18 MPa), and tangent modulus (Et = 6.4 ± 0.4 GPa) measured from coupon tests. Outer diameter and wall thickness measured via CMM on all 11 test articles. Monte Carlo propagation (N=1000 LHS samples) of combined material and geometric uncertainty yielded 95th-percentile prediction intervals that encompass experimental scatter. The UQ report appendix documents a screening sensitivity study identifying elastic modulus and screw root diameter as potentially influential; however, formal ranked sensitivity indices were not separately computed and no structured sensitivity analysis record has been linked to this package. Gradation 3 achieved on the basis of the UQ propagation; the absence of a linked sensitivity analysis object is noted.",
      "uqMethod": "Monte Carlo Latin Hypercube Sampling, N=1000",
      "uqCoverage": "Material properties (E, Sy, Et) and geometric tolerances (outer diameter, wall thickness, root radius)"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test articles from production lots with documented dimensional and material characterization. Sample representativeness confirmed by comparison to design nominal values.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs from two production lots tested across two independent laboratories. Dimensional measurements (CMM) confirm all articles within engineering drawing tolerances. Material certification records available for both lots. Sample size supports statistical comparison. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios or are demonstrated to bound the COU. Multiple load levels or configurations tested.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed under a single ASTM F1717 standard test configuration (10° off-axis compression-bending). While this configuration is the regulatory standard, only one test condition was employed. Clinically, pedicle screws experience a range of bending angles and load magnitudes. Required Gradation 3 not achieved; achieved Gradation 2. This is a known gap acknowledged in the assessment; the overall package is accepted at Medium assurance level with this noted deficiency."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) demonstrably equivalent to test article conditions. Traceability documented from test measurements to model inputs.",
      "rationale": "CMM measurements from each test article used to instantiate the corresponding FEA model geometry. Material properties from coupon tests on same production lots. Boundary conditions replicate test fixture constraints as verified by independent analyst review. Full traceability matrix available in supporting documentation. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs. Percent difference < 10% for all QoIs.",
      "rationale": "All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) satisfy both acceptance criteria. E/uval values: 0.87, 1.14, 1.61. Percent differences: 4.3%, 6.1%, 7.8%. Combined validation uncertainty (uval) accounts for experimental measurement uncertainty, inter-laboratory variability, and model input uncertainty from Monte Carlo propagation. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to the regulatory submission requirement and clinical performance criteria for pedicle screw constructs.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three quantities specified in the FDA guidance for ASTM F1717 submission. These QoIs directly characterize the structural integrity of the construct under worst-case bending loads. The COU prediction targets these same quantities. Relevance is direct and complete. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
